      %span.blg-date Tue, May 12th 2020
      %h2.index-header So far... WHAT A YEAR!
      %p Welcome back friends, it's been some time since last I wrote. The world is (at least on the surface) a much different place than it was when I last wrote in January.
      %p I have not been entirely idle, though.  I begun repracticing PHP, a language I hadn't looked at in several years, there have been some interesting changes to it, but nothing mindbogglingly different (yet).  Started playing around with PHP Composer and Laravel, for those of you familiar with Ruby, its Bundler/Gem system, and Rails, Composer and Laravel will feel a bit comfortable.
      %p Made some more progress with RSpec, starting to feel more comfortable writing my own tests as apposed to following tutorials, interestingly, took a couple of days to play with TDD in JavaScript (JEST), left that alone when I realized that I still wasn't fluent in RSpec, but it was fun to be able to apply what I know from RSpec to JEST.
      %p Now, I'm updating my blog. Specifically, I changed the Font-awesome Gem I use for this site from 'font-awesome-rails' to 'font-awesome-sass', I'd had problems with font-awesome 5 with the previous gem, not so much with swapped gem updated the icons too. Didn't take all that long to do, one commit. Oh, also to write a new post... which is what I'm doing now.
      %p I haven't forgot about my promise to start the bug tracking system, though I've put that on the back burner for the time being. I've decided to take a couple of weeks to focus on My job hunt, racking my brain for a more 'juicier project'. Oh, I've also decided to sit down and learn a "real" programming language.
      %p I've started learning C++. The purpose of my doing this is because I suspect that this will help me conceptualize programming concepts better. In addition to this, I have been reading A Common-Sense Guide to Data Structures and Algorithms, which I hope will help me become, and certainly feel, like a more competent programmer.
      %p Lastly, I've fully moved to, and am using as my daily driver, i3-gaps / tmux tools and work flow.  I have to say that while it took some time to configure it properly, and I still haven't tested a multi-monitor setup, I can't tell you what it's done for my workflow, I have almost completely stopped using my mouse, and it's amazing to be honest. Although, I have heard some amazing things about Suckless tools, specifically Suckless dwm and st. It'll be a couple of weeks before I feel like I've got time to test dwm and st out.. Been considering discontinue using Ubuntu and just use bare Debian, I don't think I'll be able to go full open source, as my laptop uses an AMD processor and the graphics drive is closed source (as far as I know). to be honest, what really bothers me is the package management system, most of my apps are installed via CLI, but then some apps are installed via SNAP and just finding out where certain files and directories are is a hassle. For example, I wanted to create a pattern in Gimp, but had trouble located the pattern's directory. After searching for the information for about 20 minutes, I came to discover that there were, in fact, two sets of pattern directories based on two different versions of Gimp, what I mean ot say that within Gimps snap system, it seemed that two versions of Gimps directory structure was there and each had its own patterns sub directory.  Then I tried to create and install the pateren folder containing the patter file within each sub directory and it rejected the operation (of course I was root).  I could go on a rant for the next couple of paragraphs, needless to say, resolved that issue in a round about way, but it seems like my file system has got a bit spaghetti like, and I don't like it.
      %p anyway, I'm going to end this post for the time being. I'll write soon.
