      %span.blg-date Thu, December 5th, 2019
      %h2.index-header Really tired, didn't want to go another day without..
      %p
        So, do you know how when you are presented with a programming problem and you think up of a solution to the problem and you spend 10 hours on it because:
      %ul
        %li You have to work within a language dialect with which you are unfamiliar.
        %ul
          %li You learn the dialect
          %li You struggle with the dialect because while you know it, it is still alien to you.
          %li You retool because if your going to work in the dialect, do some work now to make it easier down the road.
        %li You don't remember the exact syntax (grammer) to approch the problem correctly, possibly because you just spent the last 3 - 4 hours learning and working in a new dialect and your mind hasn't fully switched contexts, (say working with Ruby for 3 hours, then going to work in JavaScript, or Python or some other framework/DSL).
        %ul
          %li Go find the correct syntax
        %li You reach your solution, and it isn't clean, so you refactor
        %ul
          refactor, debug, rinse repeat
      and Voil√†, it works... but it's slow.... but it works and you move on to the next problem (relatively clean code that works, but is slower than you had expected is better than non working code).
      %p A week down the line and you discover a module that exsists for the problem you'd had a week prior, ... this module had exsisted far before you needing to tackle the problem, but this solution approches the problem from a different, and totally unseen (by the programmer) angle... and because you don't know the module... but you now know the dialect and the overall context of the problem, it only takes you a third of the time to resolve the issue (with the help of version control (Git)  of course).
      %p And your new, cleaner solution is not any faster... in fact, it might be a wee bit slower...
      %p Okay, its 12:40 in the morning. I'd like to go on, but I'm burned out for today.
      %p
        Shout outs to these people, though I'm sure that they'll never read this blog... likes on their respective social media platforms will have to suffice for the time being:
