      %span.blg-date Fri, November 22nd, 2019
      %h2.index-header It's going to be one of those weekends...
      %p A lot has happend, but not much in working on my issue tracker.
      %p So Wednesday morning, I continue with the tasks that had been given to me by the recruiter, I'm on the fifth task and I feel like I'm just about to finish it. I place all the comments for movies in a partial and have it render into the movie review page. I then begin writing the form to capture, process and save a new comment from a logged in user. there are two or three other requirements (the user can only see comments that are related to the specific movie being displayed as apposed to all the comments of all the movies in the data base. Also the restriction that the user can only write one coment per film. the User can then either edit or delete their original comment but not write an addional one.
      %p The system throws an error and I proceed to try everything I can think of the resolve the issue for an hour.  I hit all the regular sources... Google, Rails Guides, Stack overflow... I find no relevent answers to my problem.
      %p but that isn't the worst of it.  I don't work on a team, I only have myself and my text editor (and I have the internet and the whole of knowledge of human existance... yes yes... But if you're a developer you know how valuable it is to actually work with another person)  Even if the other person doesn't have the solution, or give useful feed back, it's often helpful to present a problem and just hash out opossible solutions with a real live person.
      %p but alas, it is only me. SO I began constructing a question on Stack Overflow.  I present the problem, format the bits of the files that are relevant or the cause of the problem (there were three) and then I format them on stack overflow.  Stack overflow complains that I haddn't written out the comments correctly and I proceed to wrestle with that for another 20 minutes, or so. At that point I had spent over three to four hours on this one issue and realize that what I needed was to just walk away from the code.  I was caught up in my own way of thinking about the problem and that maybe some distance from the code and the problem would help.
