      %p On Friday afternoon I recieved and email from a recruiter... which I thought was a nice change from the boiler-plate rejection emails I had usually recieved from recruiters and hiring managers and so forth...
      %p ... maybe there is something to building a portfolio website... but I digress.
      %p Moving forward, I will be refering to this recruiter using the pronouns they, them, and their to protect that person's identity, out of professional courtesy.
      %p
        Now, I fully understand the need for caution when hiring. Generally speaking, the process is expensive, time consuming, and can be filled with legal problems if the wrong person is hired, not to mention the ramifications for the people involved with hiring a person un or under qualified for a position.
        So knowing this, I fully understand and accept that finding my first position as a developer is going to be difficult.
      %p I was unsurprisingly excited when I recived the recruter's email informing me that they had shown interest in me and where interested in moving forward in the interview process, but that they wanted to get a better sence of how well I coded, therefore I was given a series of six tasks to complete, and that I was given four days to complete them from the time the email was sent.
      %p I recieved the email at 15:41 (my local time) on Friday, but didn't look at it until about an hour and a half afterwards
      %p
        The tasks I was given were contained in a Github repo and I will give basic descriptions of the tasks (in order to protect the intelectual property of said company):
      %ol
        %li
          Using an API
          %ul
            %li
              I had to pull three sets of data off of an api and apply this data to a set of pre-existing
              data, this new data could not be saved to the database.
        %li
          Building an API
          %ul
            %li
              Using the pre-existing seed data, I was to use this data to create two versions of an api.
              The second had features that extended from the first.
        %li
